Actinobacteria are well known for producing structurally diverse and medicinally important  antibiotics, such as rapamycin [1], amphotericin B [2], and avermectins [3]. However, the  discovery rate of novel natural products from soil-derived actinobacteria has remarkably  CONTACT  Zhi-Kai Guo  #these authors contributed equally to this paper. © 2018 informa uK limited, trading as taylor & francis Group   supplemental data for this article can be accessed https://doi.org/10.1080/10286020.2018.1485663 ABSTRACT One  new  flavonoid  derivative  flavoside  A  (1),  one  new  5-hydroxyanthranilic  acid  derivative  crassilin  (2),  along  with  the  known angucyclinone PD116740 (3) and oxachelin (4), was isolated  from the EtOAc extract of the fermentation broth of the sea urchin  (Anthocidaris crassispina)-derived actinobacterium, Streptomyces sp.  HD01. The structures of these compounds were established on the  basis  of  their  HR-ESI-MS  and  NMR  spectroscopic  data.  All  of  these  compounds were assessed for their antibacterial activity. reduced. The marine ecosystems harbor plentiful of unique microbes, and could provide a  tremendous opportunity for discovering novel bioactive natural products [4–6]. Therefore,  we try to isolate specific symbiotic actinobacteria from marine animals, which could allow  for the isolation of special species of actinobacteria, producing structurally unprecedented  and  biologically  active  secondary  metabolites.  In  our  continued  effort  to  discover  new  secondary  metabolites  from  under-explored  sources  [7–13],  we  investigated  an  actino- bacterium strain Streptomyces sp. HD01 from the gut of an sea urchin, Anthocidaris cras- sispina, collected from Hainan Island, China. Chemical analysis of the fermentation broth  led to the isolation and identification of one new flavonoid derivative, flavoside A (1), one  new 5-hydroxyanthranilic acid derivative, crassilin (2), as well as two known compounds,  PD116740 (3) [14] and oxachelin (4) [15] (Figure 1). All of these compounds were evaluated  for their antibacterial activity. Herein, we report the isolation, structure elucidation, and  bioactivity of these two new compounds. 2.  Results and discussion

Compound 1 was isolated as a light yellow amorphous powder with a quasimolecular ion at  m/z 499.1220 [M+Na]+, consistent with 1 showing a molecular formula of C23H24O11. The  1H NMR spectrum in DMSO-d6, combined with the analysis of HSQC data, indicated two  phenolic hydroxyl groups (δH 12.85, 10.88), five aromatic protons from δH 6.22 to δH 7.35,  five oxygenated methine protons between δH 3.25 and δH 5.21, three hydroxy groups (δH  4.64, 4.81, 4.93), six oxygenated methyl protons at δH 3.90, and three methyl protons at δH  1.08 (Table 1). Analysis of the 13C NMR and HSQC spectra allowed assigning the 14 aro- matic carbons between δC 94.8 and δC 164.9, 1 carbonyl carbon at δC 182.4, 1 methyl carbon  signal at δC 18.2, and 7 oxygen-bearing carbons from δC 56.9 to δC 102.6 that included two  oxygenated methyl carbons at δC 56.9 and an anomeric carbon at δC 102.6. The structural  information for 1 was determined by a combination of 2D NMR analysis, including HSQC,  1H-1H COSY, HMBC, and NOESY spectra, revealing a flavonoid core structure coupled with  a hexapyranose sugar group. The long-range correlation of H-1′′ (δH 5.21) to C-4′ (δC 137.7)  in the HMBC experiment established the linkage of the sugar unit to the flavone aglycone. In  the sugar group, the 1H spin systems, the correlations from H-1′′ to H-6′′ (δH 1.08) through  H-2′′ (δH 3.91), H-3′′ (δH 3.67), H-4′′ (δH 3.25), and H-5′′ (δH 4.01), were observed

δH 1.08) through  H-2′′ (δH 3.91), H-3′′ (δH 3.67), H-4′′ (δH 3.25), and H-5′′ (δH 4.01), were observed by the  1H–1H COSY spectrum. The hydroxyl groups at δH 4.93, 4.64, and 4.81 attached to C-2′′  (δC 70.7), C-3′′ (δC 71.1), and C-4′′ (δC 72.0), respectively, were identified by the  1H–1H  couplings (acquired in DMSO-d6) with H-2′′, H-3′′, and H-4′′, respectively (Figure 2). Compound  2  was  isolated  as  a  light  yellow  amorphous  powder.  The  molecular  for- mula was assigned by the HR-ESI-MS and NMR data (Table 1) as C20H31NO4. In the 1H  NMR spectrum of 2, the splitting patterns for three coupled aromatic protons (δH 7.87, d,  J = 8.8 Hz, H-3; 6.97, dd, J = 8.8, 3.0 Hz, H-4; 7.25, d, J = 3.0 Hz, H-6) revealed the presence  of a 1,2,4-trisubstituted benzene ring. In addition, the 1H NMR data of 2 (Table 1) showed  three methyl groups (δH 2.03, 3H, s, H3–9; 0.84, 6H, d, J = 6.7 Hz, H3–10′ and H3–11′) and two  exchangeable proton (δH 9.63, s, 5-OH; δH 10.11, s, 2-NH). The 13C and DEPT135 NMR  spectra revealed the presence of two carbonyl carbons (δC 166.8 and 167.8), six aromatic  carbons  at  δC  115.8–153.0,  including  three  methine  and  three  quaternary  carbons,  one  sp3 methine (δC 27.4), nine sp3 methylene (δC 25.5–64.9), and three methyl carbons (δC  22.5–24.3). The HSQC spectrum of 2 allowed all protons to be assigned to their respective  carbons and the structure of compound 2 was elucidated by the interpretation of its HMBC  and 1H–1H COSY correlations (Figure 2). In the HMBC spectrum, the correlations from  the aromatic signal H-3 to C-1 (δC 120.4) and C-5 (δC 153.0), from the aromatic signal H-6  to C-2 (δC 131.2), C-4 (δC 120.5), and the carboxyl carbon C-7 (δC 166.8) and from 2-NH  to C-1 and C-3 (δC 123.8) indicated the presence of a 1,2,4-trisubstituted benzene, which  could be also supported by the 1H–1H COSY correlation from H-3 to H-4. In addition, the  HMBC correlations from 2-NH and H3–9 to the amide carbon C-8 (δC 167.8) suggested an  N-acetyl group at the C-2 position. The last partial structure was identified as an isoundecyl  alcohol moiety which was deduced by the interpretation of the clear 1H–1H COSY corre- lations from two terminal methyl groups (H-10′ and H-11′) to a methine proton H-9′ (δH  1.49, m), from H-8′ (δH 1.13, m) to H-9′ and H-7′ (δH 1.20–1.36, m), from H-2′ (δH 1.68, m)  to H-1′ (δH 4.22, t, J = 6.5 Hz) and H-3′ (δH 1.38, m), and the overlapped COSY correlations  among the methylene protons. The connection of the isoundecyl alcohol moiety to the C-7  on the 1,2,4-trisubstituted benzene ring through an ether linkage was secured by the HMBC  correlations from the oxygenated methylene protons H-1′ to C-7. Compound 3 was isolated as a brown amorphous powder, while compound 4 was iso- lated as a white amorphous powder. Their structures were confirmed as PD116740 and  oxachelin,  respectively,  by  comparison  of  their  MS  and  NMR  data  with  those  reported  previously [14,15]. All  of  these  isolates  (1–4)  were  evaluated  for  their  antibacterial  activity  against  Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococcus pyogenes, Bacillus subtilis, Vibrio harveyi, and Vibrio  alginolyticus, using the agar diffusion method with 7-mm paper discs containing 100 μg  of compounds or rifampicin as the positive control. As a result, compounds 1–4 did not  exhibit antibacterial activity against the tested bacteria, while the positive control showed  potent activity. 3.1.  General experimental procedures

The  optical  rotation  was  measured  using  a  Rudolph  Autopol  IV  automatic  polarimeter  (Rudolph, Hackettstown, NJ, USA). The UV spectrum was obtained on a Hitachi U3000  spectrophotometer (Hitachi, Tokyo, Japan). The IR data were recorded on a Nexus 870 FT-IR  spectrometer (Nicolet, Madison, WI, USA). The high resolution mass measurement was  conducted on an Agilent 6210 TOF LC-MS instrument (Agilent, Palo Alto, CA, USA). The  1H, 13C, DEPT, and 2D NMR spectra were acquired on a Bruker DRX 600 spectrometer at  600 MHz for 1H and 150 MHz for 13C NMR (Bruker, Faellanden, Switzerland). The chemical  shifts were recorded as δ (ppm) and referenced to the solvent signal (DMSO-d6, δH at 2.50  and δC at 39.5) as the internal standard. Silica gel (200–300 mesh) for column chromatog- raphy (CC) and GF254 (10–20 μm) for thin layer chromatography (TLC) were produced  by Qingdao Marine Chemical Company, Qingdao, China, and Sephadex LH-20 from GE  Biotechnology, USA. Semi-preparative HPLC was performed on an ODS-2 Hypersil column  (5 μm, 250 × 10 mm) on an Agilent 1200 HPLC. All other chemicals used in this study  were of analytical grade. 3.2.  Strain isolation and cultivation

The strain HDa1 was isolated by one of the authors (R.W.) from the gut of an sea urchin,  Anthocidaris crassispina, collected from Hainan Island, China, using the ISP4 agar medium  (consisting of 10.0 g/L soluble starch, 1.0 g/L K2PO1,4.0 g/L MgSO4·7H2O, 1.0 g/L NaCl,  2.0 g/L (NH4)2SO2,4.0 g/L CaCO3, 0.001 g/L FeSO4·7H2O, 0.001 g/L MnCl2·7H2O, 20 g/L  agar, and deionized water, pH 7.2) supplemented with a final concentration of 50 μg/ml  potassium dichromate. It has been identified as Streptomyces sp. by 16S rRNA sequence  analysis (GenBank accession number is MG745333). A voucher specimen (HNHDa1) has  been deposited in the Institute of Tropical Bioscience and Biotechnology, Chinese Academy  of Tropical Agricultural Sciences. The strain was cultured onto Gauserime agar medium  plate (consisting of 20 g soluble starch, 1.0 g KNO3, 0.5 g MgSO4, 0.5 g K2HPO4, 0.5 g NaCl,  0.01 g FeSO4·7H2O, 20 g agar, 1 L of distilled water, pH 7.2) at 28 °C for 7 days. Agar plugs  were used to inoculate 30 × 1000 ml Erlenmeyer flasks, each containing 400 ml of liquid  medium composed of soluble starch (5.0 g/L), glucose (20.0 g/L), peptone (2.0 g/L), yeast  extract (2.0 g/L), soybean flour (10.0 g/L), NaCl (4.0 g/L), K2HPO4 (0.5 g/L), MgSO4·7H2O  (0.5 g/L), CaCO3 (2.0 g/L),

3.3.  Extraction and purification The filtrate of the fermentation broth was collected and extracted with EtOAc at room tem- perature. Then the EtOAc extract (3.8 g) was fractionated by silica gel (200–300 mesh) CC  eluted with a gradient of CHCl3/MeOH (v/v 100:0, 100:1, 100:2, 100:4, 100:8, 100:16, 100:32,  0:100)  to  give  eight  fractions  (Fr.1–8).  Fraction  2  (523  mg)  was  separated  by  Sephadex  LH-20 CC eluted with MeOH to give six subfractions (Fr.2a–2f). Fr.2b (66 mg) and Fr.2d  (84 mg) were further purified by semi-preparative HPLC with CH3OH/H2O (v/v, 70:30) to  yield 2 (3.5 mg) and 4 (5.6 mg), respectively. Fraction 3 (205 mg) was isolated by Sephadex  JOURNAL OF ASIAN NATURAL PRODUCTS RESEARCH   LH-20  CC  using  MeOH  as  eluent  to  give  five  subfractions  (Fr.3a–3e),  and  purification  of the resulting Fr.3c (57 mg) by semi-preparative HPLC with CH3OH/H2O (v/v, 75:25)  afforded 3 (3.3 mg). Fraction 4 (495 mg) was also purified by Sephadex LH-20 CC eluted  with MeOH and semi-preparative HPLC (CH3OH/H2O, v/v 60:40) to produce 1 (2.5 mg).

Antibacterial assay

The antibacterial activity of these isolated compounds was tested against the selected patho- genic bacteria, Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococcus pyogenes, Bacillus subtilis, Vibrio harveyi,  and Vibrio alginolyticus, in accordance with the previously reported method [17]. In the  assays, the antibacterial activities were tested using the agar diffusion method with 7-mm  paper discs containing 100 μg of compounds and rifampicin as the positive control. All  tested compounds were dissolved in dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). No potential conflict of interest was reported by the authors.
